  "prompt": "What are some examples of websites with great design?",
  "response": "Okay, here are some examples of websites with great design, categorized by the design principles they exemplify:\n\n**I. Visual Appeal & Aesthetics:**\n\n*   **Awwwards.com:** (Not a specific site, but a showcase of award-winning websites). This is a great place to browse cutting-edge design trends.\n\n*   **Basic Agency:** Clean, modern, and visually striking.  Uses bold typography, asymmetrical layouts, and high-quality imagery.\n\n*   **Anton & Irene:** A design agency known for its interactive and experimental websites.  Often features unique navigation and engaging animations.\n\n*   **Mikiya Kobayashi:** A furniture designer whose website is minimalist, elegant, and showcases the beauty of their products.\n\n*   **Dogstudio:**  Features immersive and interactive experiences with custom animations and transitions.\n\n**II. User Experience (UX) & Usability:**\n\n*   **Apple.com:** A classic example of clean, intuitive design.  Easy navigation, clear product presentation, and a focus on user needs.\n\n*   **Dropbox.com:** Simple and straightforward.  The landing page clearly communicates the value proposition, and the signup process is seamless.\n\n*   **Wikipedia.org:**  While not flashy, it's highly functional and easy to navigate, making information readily accessible.\n\n*   **Mailchimp.com:** Uses friendly illustrations, clear language, and a well-structured interface to make email marketing accessible to everyone.\n\n*   **Gov.uk:** A great example of accessible and user-centered design for government services.  Focuses on clarity, simplicity, and efficiency.\n\n**III. Creativity & Innovation:**\n\n*   **Active Theory:** Known for highly interactive and immersive digital experiences.  They often use WebGL and other advanced technologies to create stunning visuals and engaging interactions.\n\n*   **Resn:** Pushes the boundaries of web design with experimental layouts, animations, and interactive elements.\n\n*   **Stripe.com:** Illustrative approach.\n\n*   **Bruno Simon Portfolio:** This website looks like a browser-based game where you control a car that navigates to different sections. It's a fun and memorable way to showcase a portfolio.\n\n*   **Louis Ansa:** A visually stunning and interactive portfolio website that uses a unique 3D world to showcase projects.\n\n**IV. Storytelling & Branding:**\n\n*   **Brewdog.com:** Reflects the brand's personality and tells a compelling story.\n\n*   **Headspace.com:** Uses calming visuals and clear messaging to promote mindfulness and meditation.\n\n*   **Toms.com:** Integrates its social mission into the website design, highlighting the impact of its \"One for One\" program.\n\n**V. Minimalism & Simplicity:**\n\n*   **Google.com:** The epitome of minimalist design.\n\n*   **Medium.com:** Clean typography and a focus on content.\n\n*   **Evernote.com:** A straightforward design.\n\n**VI. Mobile-First & Responsive Design:**\n\n*   Virtually *any* modern website should be responsive, but pay attention to how well these sites adapt to different screen sizes:\n    *   **The Boston Globe:** Responsive design for easy readability.\n    *   **Shopify.com:** Excellent mobile experience.\n\n**Key Design Principles to Observe:**\n\n*   **Visual Hierarchy:** How elements are arranged to guide the user's eye.\n*   **Typography:** Font choices and how they're used.\n*   **Color Palette:** The selection and use of colors.\n*   **Imagery:** The quality and relevance of photos, illustrations, and icons.\n*   **Navigation:** How easily users can find what they're looking for.\n*   **Whitespace (Negative Space):** The empty areas that help to create balance and clarity.\n*   **Consistency:** Maintaining a consistent look and feel throughout the website.\n*   **Accessibility:** Designing for users with disabilities.\n*   **Performance:** How quickly the website loads and responds to user interactions.\n*   **Interactivity:** How users can engage with the website (animations, micro-interactions, etc.).\n\n**Where to find more inspiration:**\n\n*   **Awwwards.com:**  As mentioned before, a great resource for award-winning sites.\n*   **Dribbble.com:** A platform for designers to share their work.\n*   **Behance.net:** Adobe's platform for showcasing creative projects.\n*   **SiteInspire.com:** A curated collection of outstanding website designs.\n*   **Land-book.com:** Focuses on landing page design.\n*   **Httpster.net:** Showcases \"hub of interesting websites\".\n\nRemember that \"great design\" is subjective and depends on the specific goals of the website.  What works well for one site might not work for another.  It's important to consider the target audience, the brand, and the overall purpose of the website when evaluating its design.\n",
